Trans-abdominal ultrasound may reveal diffuse or focal mural thickening of small intestine (Figure 3.9
) (sometimes with concurrent large intestinal thickening). Definitive diagnosis is based on histopathological examination of intestinal (or rectal) biopsies (Figure 3.10
). The infiltrate may constitute a mixed cellular population, or there may be a predominance of specific cell types such that CIBD may be classified as either granulomatous enteritis/colitis or eosinophilic gastroenteritis, eosinophilic granulomatous enteritis or lymphocytic plasmacytic enteritis. Similar pathological findings are commonly identified within mesenteric lymph nodes and also occasionally in skin lesions. The condition described as multisystemic eosinophilic epitheliotropic disease may have gastrointestinal involvement as well as cutaneous, hepatic and pancreatic lesions.
